Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The core challenge in weld seam inspection lies not only in detecting defects but in ensuring that the input data is both structurally meaningful (i.e., contains a valid weld seam) and acquisition-valid (i.e., image quality is sufficient for analysis). Existing approaches typically treat pre-classification as a simple binary normal/abnormal task, often conflating structural anomalies with poor imaging conditions. Drawing inspiration from Paper 1’s bidirectional reconstruction for disentangling subtle feature variations, Paper 2’s integration of structured priors via attention mechanisms, and Paper 3’s emphasis on information-rich representation learning through supervision-aware contrastive methods, I propose a novel multi-task pre-classifier that explicitly separates *structural normality* (is this a proper weld seam?) from *acquisition validity* (is this image usable?). By introducing dual reconstruction pathways—one reconstructing normal structural priors and another modeling clean acquisition manifolds—combined with uncertainty-aware contrastive learning, the model learns to reject invalid cases more intelligently. Crucially, unlike prior works that use reconstruction for augmentation or metric learning, our method uses asymmetric reconstructions to identify which dimension (structure or quality) fails, enabling interpretable filtering. Furthermore, integrating epistemic uncertainty estimation allows the system to abstain when confidence is low, reducing false rejections in edge cases. This approach goes beyond standard pre-filtering by providing diagnostic feedback—e.g., “rejected due to blurriness” vs. “non-weld region”—which enhances deployability in industrial pipelines. It differs from referenced works by unifying disentangled reconstruction, multi-task contrastive alignment, and Bayesian uncertainty within a single pre-classification framework tailored for high-assurance manufacturing AI.

