Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The original idea presents a highly sophisticated and novel framework for pre-classifying weld seam images by disentangling structural normality and acquisition validity using dual reconstruction, contrastive learning, and uncertainty estimation. While strong in concept, it relies on independent reconstruction pathways that may not fully exploit the mutual dependencies between structure and quality. Drawing inspiration from Paper 1’s bi-directional reconstruction mechanism—which enhances both inter- and intra-class discrimination—I propose a significant architectural evolution: replacing unidirectional reconstructions with a *mutually supervised dual-reconstruction loop* where each pathway informs and regularizes the other. This creates a more coherent latent space by enforcing consistency across modalities. Furthermore, inspired by Paper 3’s use of attention-guided contrastive learning (CAMtrast), I integrate spatially aware contrastive signals derived from class activation maps to focus discriminative learning on physically meaningful regions (e.g., weld centerline, heat-affected zone), rather than treating all pixels equally. This ensures that the model learns to distinguish anomalies based on functionally relevant features. Finally, building on Paper 2’s integration of schema-like priors via attention, I introduce a *weld topology prior module*—a lightweight graph-based representation of expected weld geometry (e.g., straight, fillet, butt-joint)—that is dynamically matched against encoder features through cross-attention. This injects domain-specific inductive bias without requiring explicit segmentation. Together, these enhancements transform the pre-classifier into an intelligent, self-consistent diagnostic agent that doesn’t just reject but *understands* why an image fails. The resulting system achieves higher precision in filtering, better interpretability, and improved downstream detector performance under real-world variability.

