  "Idea": "We propose a Mutual Reconstruction and Topology-Aware Pre-Classification (MRTAP) framework for weld seam images that advances beyond conventional single-path or parallel reconstruction models by introducing a bidirectionally coupled dual-decoder architecture, spatially guided contrastive learning, and dynamic incorporation of weld structural priors. Unlike existing methods that treat structural integrity and acquisition quality as separable tasks with independent objectives, MRTAP enforces cross-task consistency through a mutually supervisory reconstruction loop: the structural decoder reconstructs geometric fidelity using edge-preserving losses, while the quality decoder restores photometric integrity; crucially, each decoder receives feedback from the other in the form of feature-level residuals used to modulate reconstruction targets. This bidirectional refinement enables the model to resolve ambiguities—such as whether a blurred region is due to motion artifact (acquisition issue) or absence of weld bead (structural anomaly)—by leveraging complementary evidence. To enhance discriminative power, we introduce Activation-Guided Contrastive Learning (AGCL), where class activation maps from intermediate layers highlight salient regions (e.g., weld seam axis) and guide the sampling of positive and negative pairs in the contrastive loss, ensuring that embeddings are pulled/pushed based on semantically meaningful areas. Additionally, we embed a Weld Topology Prior Network (WTPN)—a learnable graph schema representing common joint configurations (e.g., T-joint, lap joint)—which interacts with the shared encoder via cross-attention. During inference, WTPN matches observed features to expected topological patterns, providing soft constraints that improve generalization across unseen weld types. Uncertainty is modeled using evidential deep learning with Monte Carlo dropout, enabling the system to abstain when activation entropy exceeds a dynamic threshold calibrated per weld type. The final output includes five categories: (1) Valid, (2) Structurally Abnormal, (3) Acquisition-Invalid, (4) Topology-Mismatch (suggesting misalignment or wrong workpiece), and (5) High-Uncertainty (abstain). This granular, interpretable diagnosis allows not only efficient filtering but also actionable feedback for robotic welding systems. By integrating mutual reconstruction, attention-guided contrastive learning, and topological reasoning, MRTAP shifts pre-classification from passive rejection to active understanding, significantly improving robustness and trustworthiness in industrial inspection pipelines.",
